lego:evidence  a  owl:AnnotationProperty .

gomodel:SYNGO_5391  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 1-3: Nogo-A (gene RTN4) inhibition through a specific antibody, as well as inhibition of its receptors NgR (gene RTN4R) and S1PR2, affects dendritic spine development in CA3 pyramidal neurons. Confocal imaging after application showed spine density and morphology was significantly affected. This was confirmed by FRAP of eGFP-actin in spines.. Experimental description: M&M: \"Hippocampal organotypic cultures were prepared from postnatal day 5 (P5) C57Bl/6 mice of either sex as previously described (Stoppini et al., 1991; Michaelsen-Preusse et al., 2014).\"\n\n\"The loss-of-function for the Nogo-A signaling was obtained using:\n(1) a monoclonal Nogo-A specific, function blocking antibody, against an 18-aa peptide in the most active region of Nogo-A (mouse IgG1, 11C7; Oertle et al., 2003; Liebscher et al., 2005; Maier et al., 2009; gift from Novartis Pharma AG, Basel, Switzerland to Martin Schwab);\n(2) a function-blocking antibody against the Nogo receptor NgR (goat anti-Nogo receptor affinity-purified goat IgG; R&D Systems);\n(3) a specific blocker for the sphingosine-1-phosphate receptor 2 (S1PR2; JTE-013; Tocris, 5 μM in DMSO);\n(4) a selective inhibitor of the Rho-associated protein kinase p160ROCK (Y27632 dihydrochloride, Tocris, 100 uM in H2O);\n(5) the specific actin stabilizing agent Jasplakinolide (Tocris, 0.2 uM in DMSO).\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2023-03-15" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5391" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

